description.narrative:
&nbsp;Project funding of ECO-V comes under the intervention area&nbsp;of Sustainable development and climate justice. The overall goal is enhancing conscious consumerism to combat Climate change focusing mainly on food safety.
Problem analysis- Climate change adaptation is not discussed widely among Sri Lankan citizens at grass root level. Still there is no proper understanding of climate change repercussions and environmental sustainability. Due to lack of training and availability of simple strategic information many organisations are reluctant to address this topic in their project area.
Expected results are Lifestyles of stakeholder groups has changed positively and more conscious in consumerism and operational body established at National level to continue work on this streamline.
Objective are to change food consumption pattern among 5 selected stakeholder groups, To establish an operational body with a mandate of long term plan working towards climate Change, conscious consumerism and working towards Sustainable Development and also To publish a booklet on safe food and conscious consumerism as a guide to adopt climate.
This project will be focused on sensitising stakeholder groups of excisting Diakonia partner networks and organization including Youth, children, Women, at Kandy, Colombo and Galle on food safety and sustainable life style to combat Climate Change. This will be achieved through establishing an operating body based at ECO-V focused on addressing this issue as a long term programme to direct public in conscious consumerism to combat Climate change at National level with trained resources persons. ECO-V will measure the change among those stakeholders and will use the project outcomes to strengthen the National level operating body on conscious consumerism. Since most of the outputs/outcomes will be on behavioural change.&nbsp;Eco-V will be using more qualitative analysis and some quantitative analysis to measure the success of the project.
Mainstreaming components are environment and Gender.
